snippet.textDisplay:
Sekiro is one of the most-refined gameplay experiences I've ever had.  It's entirely uncompromising in it's execution and the level and encounter design is second to none.

Progression comes in the form of both in-game skills and progression of the skill of player himself.

Breaking an enemy's posture and moving in for that final deathblow feels as satisfying at hour fifty as it did at hour five and that says a LOT about the game's precise design.  FromSoft is, as far as I'm concerned, the best in the business right now when it comes to gameplay, encounter and level design.
snippet.textOriginal:
Sekiro is one of the most-refined gameplay experiences I've ever had.  It's entirely uncompromising in it's execution and the level and encounter design is second to none.

Progression comes in the form of both in-game skills and progression of the skill of player himself.

Breaking an enemy's posture and moving in for that final deathblow feels as satisfying at hour fifty as it did at hour five and that says a LOT about the game's precise design.  FromSoft is, as far as I'm concerned, the best in the business right now when it comes to gameplay, encounter and level design.

snippet.textDisplay: Spent 24 hours playing this game now. This could have very well be one of the best games of all times, would it not be for its unfair combat system. Challenging, I get that. Learning enemies moves sets, I get that. Learning to time your parries, I get that. However,  this games' RNG and its camera angles oftentimes render your skillset useless. Combine that with the fact the learning curve for said skillset is too steep in my opinion. I must, admit, it's all very clever. This games brings about an inner struggle of wanting to continue vs wanting to quit like I have seldom experienced. I just don't find it worth my time any more. Adfter all, this is still a video game.

The animations don't match up with what the game is actually doing.  The stealth is terrible.  The lock camera has a life of its own and turns off mid combat.  The more you die the more it takes from you to the point where starting a new game is easier than trying to aquire the stuff it took.  Honestly, if this was released 20 years ago it would have been panned.

snippet.textDisplay: Hello everyone.First and foremost,this game was designed for the hard core gamer in mind.This game is not for the feint of heart.You have to be a patient person to really enjoy this game...this game is all about blocking and waiting for the right moment to strike your enemy for that finishing blow...you must have a strategy in place before you take on any sub-boss and main boss otherwise you will die often out of frustration.I love this game so much it reminds me a lot like Tenchu.In fact this game is exactly how a new tenchu game would of been like..I loved the tenchu series and love Japanese history so this was the perfect game for me.i finished the game on my 3rd playthrough with 96% trophies üèÜ. This is a well crafted ninja action adventure game.Beautiful graphics and sound and your like me who loves ancient japan sengoku/feudal times u will love Sekiro.

snippet.textDisplay:
I love the Souls series and difficult games in general, but think ive met my match with Sekiro. I was doing well until i came up against the first Shinobi Hunter miniboss called "Enshin" at Hirata estate. 

Im simply too slow at reacting to the perilous attacks. I see the symbol, i start thinking "is it a sweep, thrust, or grab"? and by the time ive thought about it ive been murdered. 

Recently i was playing an old classic "Alex Kidd in miracle world" (which i completed when i was a kid), I couldn't get anywhere on it this time. im only 37, but i think my reactions are shot :|
Are there any old gits like me who have beat this game? Id hate to hang up my controller, but im starting to consider it :(

snippet.textDisplay:
If anyone is contemplating buying this game, you definitely should.
Sekiro is a masterpiece, I've played all of the dark souls, bloodborne, and some other great games like the witcher 3, nioh, monster hunter, dmc and more, this game is all pure quality in and out, but I've never experienced such satisfying and enjoyable combat. At times through certain bosses it felt like I'm swinging the sword and not sekiro. It can be tough at first but there's one boss midgame that will MAKE you master it's combat.
snippet.textOriginal:

Sekiro is a masterpiece, I've played all of the dark souls, bloodborne, and some other great games like the witcher 3, nioh, monster hunter, dmc and more, this game is all pure quality in and out, but I've never experienced such satisfying and enjoyable combat. At times through certain bosses it felt like I'm swinging the sword and not sekiro. It can be tough at first but there's one boss midgame that will MAKE you master it's combat.

snippet.textDisplay:
Hardest things about "Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice"
1. The camera both manual and auto centering.
2. collision detection with enemies
3. auto connect / targeting both yours and the enemies. nothing like watching an enemy rotate 360 degrees without shuffling a single step or change in stance just to connect and hit you. Thanks animators!
4.buffering when your simply using health... thanks design leads... ...! its like watching someone crack open a pepsi while a tiger is mauling their face off.
other then that this is the best memory game I have ever experienced.
snippet.textOriginal:
Hardest things about "Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice"
1. The camera both manual and auto centering.
2. collision detection with enemies
3. auto connect / targeting both yours and the enemies. nothing like watching an enemy rotate 360 degrees without shuffling a single step or change in stance just to connect and hit you. Thanks animators!
4.buffering when your simply using health... thanks design leads... ...! its like watching someone crack open a pepsi while a tiger is mauling their face off.
other then that this is the best memory game I have ever experienced.

snippet.textDisplay: Does anyone recommend serkio to a souls player? Quick backstory, I‚Äôve played and beaten every soulsborne game without summons (expect ds2 I never found that it pulled me in, like the rest of the soulsborne games) I‚Äôve beaten ds1 twice, getting both endings, I‚Äôve beaten bloodborne twice as well, and I‚Äôve beaten ds3 about 5 times, getting only two of the endings. I‚Äôm looking for more because these games are masterpieces, but I‚Äôve heard serkio is different, as in mechanically, dodging wont cut it, and ether will back stepping, but there are other changes too (mechanically) but I‚Äôm also glad there is no relaying on shields, as first off I‚Äôm pretty sure there are no shields in serkio, and second I don‚Äôt use shields at all in soulsborne games. I also have an semi aggressive play style that might hold account in serkio, me having that type of play style works very well with me (especially bloodborne) I use it mostly in bosses as I have quite quick reflexes, me using this type of play style almost never punishes me. So what is the take on serkio? Is it worth it?

snippet.textDisplay: This game is better than souls series. I love the single player and the technical combat.  I love deflecting and the posture system. Deathblows on bosses feel super rewarding when you deflect all of their hits and you find out how to get their posture down. Dark souls combat was repetative and boring. Hit Dodge block and stamina bar. Nioh was bad too and the worst thing about it was that the enemies kept being recycled and you would find yourself fighting the same enemies and bosses but scaled to a different power level. Souls fans hate this game (according to reviews I've read on metacritic) and it's because they're viewing it in the lens of a souls game. It's a whole different game and better than souls

snippet.textDisplay:
To the people who played this game, how difficult is it?
I'm from the PS1 generation, and although I'm in my mid 30s and still play games every once in a while, I've lost the spirit of perseverance. If a game is too difficult, I simply put it aside and never play it again. There's also the fact that I'm not as skilled as before. 
I played Onmiusha, all three installments when they first came out. I also played Shinobi on the PS2, but it was too difficult for me.

snippet.textDisplay:
Wow, colored me impressed, IGN actually has a better review than some of the metacric reviews. It actually goes into some game mechanics! My only criticism would be its score and other left out flaws. 

There are WAY too many bosses with mobs or grunt enemies. This makes those fights frustrating, as you always want to focus on the boss but the weaker enemies keep getting in your way. Obviously its designed for you to take out the weaker enemies first, but your very likely to die to the boss many times if its your first time fighting it, so you'll have to kill the mobs all over again every time you die.

A big pet peeve of mine is bonfires (or in this case shrines) that are too close to enemy spawns. This happens a lot in Sekiro (so far), surprising given this is their 6th game that uses a "bonfire" mechanic. 

The art design is beautiful, but individual textures can be bad at times. If you don't notice that sort of thing, you probably won't here. BUT, there is a frame rate issue. It will lower at times for me, no matter the graphical setting, so if going under 60 fps really bothers you, you may not like it. 

Last thing to mention, and it might just be me, but Ive gotten some slight motion sickness when I have motion blur on. Again his might just be me, Ive been prone to motion sickness before, and it only happens when I turn motion blur on and play for several hours.

At this point I would rate it maybe an 7.5-8/10, well above average but not without it's flaws. But I need more time with it to properly rate it.

The art design is beautiful, but individual textures can be bad at times. If you don't notice that sort of thing, you probably won't here. BUT, there is a frame rate issue. It will lower at times for me, no matter the graphical setting, so if going under 60 fps really bothers you, you may not like it. 

Last thing to mention, and it might just be me, but Ive gotten some slight motion sickness when I have motion blur on. Again his might just be me, Ive been prone to motion sickness before, and it only happens when I turn motion blur on and play for several hours.

At this point I would rate it maybe an 7.5-8/10, well above average but not without it's flaws. But I need more time with it to properly rate it.

snippet.textDisplay:
A souls-type game without any loot??
Don't get me wrong this game looks awesome and i've been waiting for it since the first trailer came out, but a huge part of what make these types of games fun is to collect sweet armors and weapons and building your character to work around them.. Why would I even jump into NG+ if there's nothing left for me to collect or I can't even keep building my character...
Prostethic arm and grappling looks fun, but I would trade that for proper loot and character creation anytime.
snippet.textOriginal:
A souls-type game without any loot??
Don't get me wrong this game looks awesome and i've been waiting for it since the first trailer came out, but a huge part of what make these types of games fun is to collect sweet armors and weapons and building your character to work around them.. Why would I even jump into NG+ if there's nothing left for me to collect or I can't even keep building my character...
Prostethic arm and grappling looks fun, but I would trade that for proper loot and character creation anytime.

snippet.textDisplay: I think its gonna be a hard pass from me. It might be polished but, the gameplay no longer appeals to me. Monster Hunter World was a great game that I just couldn't get into. No stats, no leveling, just gear, and endless grind to get it. In SDT, you have no stats and there's no reason to have em, you're stuck with the same armor and weapon the entire game. So its like Monster Hunter except you only get one class, one weapon, and one armor. It might work beautifully, and I hope the game is successful but on this iteration I'll pass. Hope the rest of you enjoy it though.
snippet.textOriginal: I think its gonna be a hard pass from me. It might be polished but, the gameplay no longer appeals to me. Monster Hunter World was a great game that I just couldn't get into.
